Doc,<br><br>
There were no fraggings that were excusable. No matter how lousy some of the leaders were. I am not convinced that murders which occurred in Vietnam were committed solely by disgruntled subordinates.<br><br>
I think if you take into account the amount of weaponry that was available, one could commit murder and get away with it fairly easily.<br><br>
Sometimes one wonders if murders were committed in order to cover up crimes that had been discovered. There was much underground and black market activity. Turf wars?<br><br>
There were times that we were mortared with 81mm mortar rounds - which were Nato type ammunition. We could tell by the 81mm tail fin assemblies that we policed up. The enemy was issued 82mm. Somebody was supplying our enemy. I wonder who?<br><br>
Our troops had many different enemies. Maybe even from our own side?<br><br>
At any rate alot of dirty dealings were done and some of the fraggings could have occurred when somone knew something that he shouldn't have known.<br><br>

